---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const features = [
  { href: "/docs/architecture/", title: "godex harness", body: "Event bus, JSONL journal, runner, providers, and tools as one composable core." },
  { href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Extensibility", body: "Fork the harness, embed the CLI, ship MCPs and skills, or wait for compiled Go addons." },
  { href: "/docs/event-bus/", title: "Event bus", body: "Every state transition is a typed event. TUI, plugins, replay, and RL all subscribe to the same stream." },
  { href: "/docs/tools/", title: "Built-in tools", body: "Shell, edit, patch, search, git, LSP, MCP, memory, todo, subagent, download." },
  { href: "/docs/mcp/", title: "MCP integration", body: "Stdio MCP servers attached per session, exposed as mcp.<server>.<tool> in the registry." },
  { href: "/docs/acp/", title: "Agent Client Protocol", body: "Run gode as an ACP agent over stdio for any compliant client." },
  { href: "/docs/app-server/", title: "App server", body: "Codex-style JSON-RPC over stdio or WebSocket for desktop control." },
  { href: "/docs/sessions/", title: "Sessions & resume", body: "Disk-backed sessions you can list, search, and pick up where you left off." },
  { href: "/docs/goal-mode/", title: "Goal mode", body: "Long-running goals with subagents, todos, and structured progress." },
  { href: "/docs/tui/", title: "TUI", body: "Bubble Tea + Lip Gloss interface with composable view models." },
  { href: "/docs/desktop/", title: "Gode Desktop", body: "Native Electron app with embedded terminal and browser, talking to gode over the app-server." },
];
---

<Layout title="gode · Go-native coding agent harness">
  <section class="container">
    <div class="hero">
      <img class="logo" src="/logo.png" alt="gode logo" />
      <h1 class="wordmark">gode</h1>
      <p class="tagline">
        A Go-native TUI coding agent and event-driven agent harness.
        Open-source infrastructure for building, training, and running coding agents.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/docs/install/">Install</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/docs/acp/">ACP guide</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <pre><code>$ go run ./cmd/gode
$ go run ./cmd/gode resume
$ go run ./cmd/gode acp --provider mock --auto-approve
$ go run ./cmd/gode app-server --listen ws://127.0.0.1:0</code></pre>

    <h2>What gode is</h2>
    <p>
      <code>gode</code> wraps an internal harness called <code>godex</code> that owns the moving parts of a
      coding agent: sessions, tools, workspace state, MCP connections, context management,
      provider adapters, and an event bus that everything else hangs off of.
    </p>
    <p>
      The goal is to give ML labs and tool builders a solid open base to train, evaluate,
      and run coding agents without re-implementing the surrounding plumbing each time.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Alpha.</strong> Packages, commands, configuration, and event formats may move,
      break, or disappear. There are no API guarantees yet.
    </div>

    <h2>Explore</h2>
    <div class="features">
      {features.map((f) => (
        <a class="feature-card" href={f.href}>
          <h3>{f.title}</h3>
          <p>{f.body}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h2>Why an event bus?</h2>
    <p>
      Coding agents are systems, not scripts. Tool calls, message deltas, permission
      requests, and workspace mutations all need to fan out to the UI, the journal,
      external observers, and replay infrastructure at the same time. gode treats every
      meaningful state transition as a typed event on a shared bus, so subscribing a new
      consumer — a new view, an OpenTelemetry exporter, an RL replay buffer — is a small
      change rather than a refactor.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>OpenAI / Codex provider with multi-turn tool result continuation.</li>
      <li>Anthropic Claude Go adapter (in progress).</li>
      <li>Stdio MCP servers, with HTTP and SSE transports planned.</li>
      <li>ACP and Codex-style app-server transports for external control.</li>
      <li>OpenTelemetry tracing wired through the runner; Jaeger ready out of the box.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Layout>
